<subSubSection id="9BC5A0F3A58DF95FFDCA3E242764C140" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A6894F52CD3EE63BB29FA6A610C88917" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C87F98F6E81D016CF4156FCD00AA7F2B" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
The specific name, 
<taxonomicName id="D8D2A5554C1E2BE300F57231B355F589" authorityName="Shiraki &amp; Shimomura &amp; Kakui" authorityYear="2022" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Deltanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deltanthura palpus" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="palpus">
<emphasis id="6674E4D368DE321EA9C0A46F59BBC527" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Deltanthura palpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Latin: palp), is a singular noun in the nominative case, referring to the presence of a mandibular palp, a unique trait in paranthurid neotenous genera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0C5D034A81FBCC3F5C7909968CD86EC1" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="description">
<paragraph id="CC93877EF73285EBA9366BA2BC5BA74D" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Description of holotype female.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="83E9DDA9C4BFCD88FA26CFF5F43D033F" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Body relatively slender (Figs 
<figureCitation id="D89AA663F710A8496788DA9CE3F3B04D" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female, lateral view of fixed specimen. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666141" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="891E0520621A2BA015348AA1E80E95E4" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2A-C</figureCitation>
), length 7.69 times width. Head (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AFB0020ADF8B3E08A3CCD0A2E8872AAF" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2A</figureCitation>
) length 1.02 times head width, roughened, irregular dorsally; rostrum protruding as much as anterolateral lobes; eyes dorsolateral, with scattered ommatidia. Pereonites 1-7 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="06E141A2247C01A63DC4C561D1BE2272" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2A, B</figureCitation>
) roughened, irregular dorsally, with length ratio 1.00:1.02:1.26:1.19:1.08:0.78:0.18; pereonite 7 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AFE4FC459E9B97E4F801A301F42F1CF5" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2B, C</figureCitation>
) reduced, hidden laterally, lacking pereopod 7. Pleonites 1-5 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BB587B0A22E1DA96C1F2730755220028" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2B, C</figureCitation>
) fused but with sutures, length 0.06 times body length. Pleonite 6 entirely fused dorsally to telson (Figs 
<figureCitation id="3DA4E29A9A34FC56ED64DA6740CE10D6" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2B, C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="083ABFF142AABF136A798C253CC62E7E" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-E. Left pleopods 1 - 5 (most setal ornamentation omitted); F. Right uropod; G. Left uropodal exopod; H. Telson. Scale bars: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666144" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">4H</figureCitation>
); pleotelson triangular, length 1.04 times width, with four dorsal and six apical simple setae.
</paragraph>
<caption id="B3E1E7F521DF8DC5F0610C7C70F281AC" doi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666141" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
<paragraph id="39509E338E32150E3077B253CF98D038" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis id="3A0D79BBFB28E5781A8E99BC5BC9A88B" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Figure 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="66DD62392712B75DF9E269EB99727177" authorityName="Shiraki &amp; Shimomura &amp; Kakui" authorityYear="2022" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Deltanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deltanthura palpus" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="palpus">
<emphasis id="541F96734AC76B5174AB641BEA444C12" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Deltanthura palpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., holotype, female, lateral view of fixed specimen. Scale bar: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="046D2A9DBFAD302B689857A939E490C4" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Antennula (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="22898391F837D4C407A869E62BA58DFD" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2D</figureCitation>
) with three peduncular and six flagellar articles. Peduncular article 1 with one inner and two outer plumose sensory setae; article 2 with inner simple seta; article 3 with three inner and one outer simple setae. Flagellar articles 1 and 2 naked; article 3 with distal aesthetasc and three distal simple setae; article 4 with distal aesthetasc; article 5 with distal aesthetasc and simple seta; article 6 with four distal simple setae.
</paragraph>
<caption id="CC55670AD9431E4782D9286537FBB282" doi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="8BC2D4B0E5B4BC4EE78CCB3B31DCF285" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis id="804306AA027D75EA9104A1880912A6F0" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Figure 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1380157E52C1360C4DC040AA0ECFE2C4" authorityName="Shiraki &amp; Shimomura &amp; Kakui" authorityYear="2022" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Deltanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deltanthura palpus" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="palpus">
<emphasis id="EE225B0B7F84490D6289263088051E14" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Deltanthura palpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., holotype, female. 
<emphasis id="D41B947823DD82535497C88A128F9F22" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">A.</emphasis>
Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; 
<emphasis id="337E23A0AE358F405FF8CD022236BDCA" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">B.</emphasis>
Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; 
<emphasis id="9F75A8B46F462433BE92BA13D27A1134" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">C.</emphasis>
Lateral view; 
<emphasis id="CDD3F12725E83E2A1249B2772197E302" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">D.</emphasis>
Left antennula; 
<emphasis id="295A6112E84D527F3623DF9B14AF42C1" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">E.</emphasis>
Left antenna; 
<emphasis id="06B83A236202AD06FC2AC7714F182582" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">F.</emphasis>
Right mandible; 
<emphasis id="29C10F799C1585DBE2B99E330A5AAB73" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">G.</emphasis>
Right maxilla; 
<emphasis id="9A46C85B3BFE1BD1239AEAB3439C6E13" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">H.</emphasis>
Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (
<emphasis id="A00E26EB582905BE9BB35AF3097FB2DC" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">A-C</emphasis>
); 100 
<normalizedToken id="664366200906AB3CAF48A203F8B99D2F" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(
<emphasis id="5DCC834A3B503A256E24D61A73A13F73" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">D-H</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="EB1B4ED3B1F601EBF21CB00CF36255C6" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Antenna (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FDDBFE4DC7B4281E6EC2622C5B8E0FA6" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2E</figureCitation>
) with five peduncular and nine flagellar articles. Peduncular article 1 with outer simple seta; article 2 with two distal simple setae; article 3 with two inner simple setae; article 4 with two distal plumose sensory setae and three simple setae; article 5 with four distal plumose sensory setae and four inner simple setae. Flagellar articles 1-9 with four, four, seven, four, three, three, two, four and zero distal simple setae, respectively.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B7D2D502C313DFF64F154183308EAC5" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Mandible (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8B0E283BD1E5B7CEAABE0E61A4A9D71C" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2F</figureCitation>
) with 3-articulate palp. Palp article 1 naked; article 2 with distal simple seta; article 3 with eleven simple setae. Molar absent. Incisor acute.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="09148D68BB1AFC1068E3A893A4DE832E" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Maxilla (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0E98618253B33C4A1E9E6313B3B7F2A9" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2G</figureCitation>
) slender, with twelve teeth and narrow lamella.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="34DAC63928AF13682CA02492F887A553" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Maxilliped (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9F997DA64883734E0C0B02345233B54F" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A. Dorsal view of head and pereonite 1; B. Dorsal view from pereonite 2 to telson; C. Lateral view; D. Left antennula; E. Left antenna; F. Right mandible; G. Right maxilla; H. Right maxilliped. Scale bars: 1 mm (A-C); 100 µm (D-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666142" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">2H</figureCitation>
) with 4-articulate palp. Palp articles 1 and 2 long, 3 and 4 short, with one, four, one, and three simple setae, respectively. Endite present, reaching middle of article 2, with distal simple seta. Epipod oval.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3FF4881A19B1604B42A510A45DCD5D1D" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Pereopod 1 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B2337540FF30566959C37BA6633346E5" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-F. Left pereopods 1 - 6. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666143" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">3A</figureCitation>
) subchelate, robust. Basis with three dorsal plumose sensory setae and ventrodistal seta (tip broken). Ischium with one outer and one ventrodistal simple setae. Merus with two dorsal, one outer, and one ventral simple setae. Carpus strongly protruding ventrodistally, with three inner mid-ventral spiniform setae and four simple setae. Propodus broad, with two inner proximal spiniform setae, and one outer, four dorsal, and one distal simple setae. Palm with five outer spiniform setae and seven simple setae. Dactylus and unguis fused, with two ventral and five middle simple setae.
</paragraph>
<caption id="9963CD6FE64CE0CE0E8C3A56D4EEAC87" doi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666143" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="A11374B1B49EF9D5998A48F18DB0DFF7" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis id="010626F72B87DAEE6BDDFA8680A5410E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Figure 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="27A6903DA9CAEB4F107690DA62ECF2DE" authorityName="Shiraki &amp; Shimomura &amp; Kakui" authorityYear="2022" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Deltanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deltanthura palpus" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="palpus">
<emphasis id="74A4F9B833CF16A8B02B1EFE3FE717E0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Deltanthura palpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., holotype, female. 
<emphasis id="0FB9D12CF48A618449EC72D8F98B98B0" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">A-F.</emphasis>
Left pereopods 1-6. Scale bar: 100 
<normalizedToken id="45B0CC46AA6DC3809FD5DC0E787C89F9" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="7A72E54DDDEF578747181C0FDE9CBE01" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Pereopod 2 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="803352BBF10948180B81457478259D70" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-F. Left pereopods 1 - 6. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666143" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">3B</figureCitation>
) narrow. Basis with two dorsal plumose sensory setae, two simple setae, and dorsal seta (tip broken). Ischium with three simple setae. Merus with two dorsal and two ventrodistal simple setae. Carpus triangular, longer than wide, with three ventrodistal simple setae and ventrodistal seta (tip broken). Propodus with dorsal plumose sensory seta, three ventral spiniform setae, and two dorsal and three ventral simple setae. Dactylus with ventrodistal thick seta and three ventral, three ventrodistal, and four inner distal simple setae. Unguis naked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9CFDF19C6F19F92DA2B1004FE4BFE5B1" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Pereopod 3 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="23A4C21F458CA70656E2CA5CDDAA64D8" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-F. Left pereopods 1 - 6. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666143" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">3C</figureCitation>
) similar to pereopod 2 except in number of setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BE8BD29DE4E0584F3802A47BDF5D6B47" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Pereopods 4-6 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D605930DE48DA3005FDF3EB68CF7C19D" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-F. Left pereopods 1 - 6. Scale bar: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666143" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">3D-F</figureCitation>
) narrower than pereopod 2, but similar to it except in number of setae and shape of carpus. Carpus rectangular, with ventrodistal spiniform seta.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E27A577BA542F4CB08AF2BCDF40C75F7" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Pleopod 1 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A093967B2D164EFC3F694DECC4A23621" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-E. Left pleopods 1 - 5 (most setal ornamentation omitted); F. Right uropod; G. Left uropodal exopod; H. Telson. Scale bars: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666144" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">4A</figureCitation>
) protopod with inner simple seta and outer seta (tip broken). Exopod operculiform, distal margin serrate, with 15 marginal plumose setae and four simple setae on surface. Endopod 0.53 times longer than exopod, with three distal simple setae.
</paragraph>
<caption id="D5D0C1AF2E21EA9E8AA8B86659A65F7E" doi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666144" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph id="D60563A88BA5AB16F799953B874A459C" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis id="3AFEAA87ADC949CF38CCC661BFDAFD99" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Figure 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="FAD0E80A8CA1EF61EA036EA7D03B2509" authorityName="Shiraki &amp; Shimomura &amp; Kakui" authorityYear="2022" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Deltanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deltanthura palpus" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="palpus">
<emphasis id="613C17BECD64CA34160C4FEBA7A88F76" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Deltanthura palpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., holotype, female. 
<emphasis id="7671681F1789C8B4CA34CE875FC8DCBC" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">A-E.</emphasis>
Left pleopods 1-5 (most setal ornamentation omitted); 
<emphasis id="2A8387F1FCB0AA44DA1FF75D690AEFD3" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">F.</emphasis>
Right uropod; 
<emphasis id="AAA5E9ACE00C297C9065A39F181D2190" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">G.</emphasis>
Left uropodal exopod; 
<emphasis id="45F103E31A070B666C41DA9D10818466" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">H.</emphasis>
Telson. Scale bars: 100 
<normalizedToken id="D4233CBC379FCDF64F5235DC025459D2" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="A3B538BD975614F69BE0A2830DEB87AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Pleopods 2-5 (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E3305580F1498EDD7170BA4C5BD2B090" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-E. Left pleopods 1 - 5 (most setal ornamentation omitted); F. Right uropod; G. Left uropodal exopod; H. Telson. Scale bars: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666144" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">4B-E</figureCitation>
) similar to one another. Protopod with one or two simple setae. Exopod with five to seven distal plumose setae and outer simple (pleopods 2-4) or plumose (pleopod 5) seta. Endopod with three distal plumose setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="20176010B73C9BBEE681B3A10DF4C1AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Uropod (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="25F9E8197E79079446DD12E543646985" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female. A-E. Left pleopods 1 - 5 (most setal ornamentation omitted); F. Right uropod; G. Left uropodal exopod; H. Telson. Scale bars: 100 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666144" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">4F, G</figureCitation>
) with protopod bearing two outer and one inner plumose setae and outer simple seta. Exopod elongate triangular, tapering, with five (right) and 10 (left) simple setae. Endopod with two distal projections, five outer and three distal plumose sensory setae, and 12 distal simple setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8CCA5CC9D83994235051DB02ABD581AD" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="B1355B41DFA58BCD911251BDFD36C144" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB768529ABF2913092BBD89905CD8700" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Our specimen lacks oostegites and an appendix masculina, but its pereon is expanded ventrally (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AFDD3218950137516C056D958D5F081B" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Deltanthura palpus sp. nov., holotype, female, lateral view of fixed specimen. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.98.81772.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/666141" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">1</figureCitation>
), leading us to conclude that it is a female prior to spawning, rather than a manca-stage individual. The strongly reduced pereonite 7 also supports this conclusion; this segment is not as reduced as in the mancae of non-neotenous species (cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="144539ABE322EB49A7C1C6504628C2B2" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2971.1.2" author="Frutos, I" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="17 - 32" refId="B3" refString="Frutos, I, Sorbe, JC, Junoy, J, 2011. The first blind Paranthura species (Crustacea, Isopoda, Paranthuridae) from the 'El Cachucho' Marine Protected Area (Le Danois Bank, southern Bay of Biscay). Zootaxa 2971 (1): 17 - 32, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2971.1.2" title="The first blind Paranthura species (Crustacea, Isopoda, Paranthuridae) from the ' El Cachucho' Marine Protected Area (Le Danois Bank, southern Bay of Biscay)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2971.1.2" volume="2971" year="2011">Frutos et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 2C, D; 
<bibRefCitation id="0E12278734DC1DB50BAFFF5AA49F8B79" author="Waegele, JW" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="113 - 159" refId="B18" refString="Waegele, JW, 1981. Study of the Anthuridae (Crustacea: Isopoda: Anthuridea) from the Mediterranean and the Red Sea. Israel. Journal of Zoology 30 (3): 113 - 159" title="Study of the Anthuridae (Crustacea: Isopoda: Anthuridea) from the Mediterranean and the Red Sea. Israel." volume="30" year="1981">
<normalizedToken id="38E32C996A74AD2505421ACD632C07B4" originalValue="Wägele">Waegele</normalizedToken>
1981
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 9M). This is the fifth neotenous genus known in 
<taxonomicName id="7C88659E9FE26759AE3A88C2934AEFE6" authorityName="Menzies &amp; Glynn" authorityYear="1968" class="Malacostraca" family="Paranthuridae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Paranthuridae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6B1E943155604998941127AD5F663D0C" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
<taxonomicName id="639E9EEF35F1E0E00F87631348CFE2E1" authorityName="Shiraki &amp; Shimomura &amp; Kakui" authorityYear="2022" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Deltanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deltanthura palpus" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="palpus">
<emphasis id="103554DDA70966AC406D1140AD7C5D5C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Deltanthura palpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. et sp. nov. differs from 
<taxonomicName id="7AAAE81DBE9CD74312BF5884C8038203" authorityName="Kensley &amp; Heard" authorityYear="1991" class="Malacostraca" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Califanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Califanthura minuta" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="6BD08F71BF6A8ABB16E093FF418AD3D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Califanthura minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which may belong in 
<taxonomicName id="0F513759FD56519462C542573B52B33F" authorityName="Shiraki &amp; Shimomura &amp; Kakui" authorityYear="2022" family="Paranthuridae" genus="Deltanthura" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Deltanthura" order="Isopoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="44AA97771D86D158DBFFD1AD6C13599A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Deltanthura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Remarks above for the genus), in the following characters (character state of 
<taxonomicName id="50F3C09CF34C0BDD80141DE8F62D3B5D" genus="C." lsidName="C. minuta" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="707BDCF28B932212CA93E0744113F405" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">C. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in parenthesis): body length 7.03 mm (1.60 mm); carpus of pereopod 1 strongly protruding ventrodistally (not protruding); endopod of pleopod 1 short, about half length of exopod (elongate, slightly shorter than exopod); and uropodal endopod with two distal projections (no projections).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
